So we can take proper advantage of `@Isolated` testing.

The easy part is to use the `@Test` from `org.junit.jupiter.api.*` package.

The difficult ones are changing `@Test(expected = TestException.class)`

into

```java
import org.junit.jupiter.api.Test;
import static org.junit.jupiter.api.Assertions.assertThrows;

@Test
void shouldThrowException() {
    assertThrows(TestException.class, () -> {
        // code that is expected to throw Exception (or subclass)
    });
}
```
